      <ObservedData ID="133657826">
        <Attribute Type="Description">In a male fetus with Schneckenbecken dysplasia (SHNKND; 269250), Furuichi et al. (2009) identified homozygosity for a 4,959-bp deletion (IVS6+730_IVS7+3171del4959) within the SLC35SD1 gene, resulting in complete removal of exon 7 and generation of a premature stop codon. The first-cousin Turkish parents were heterozygous carriers of the deletion. The breakpoints in intron 6 and intron 7 were flanked by 11-bp direct repeats and only 1 repeat was retained, suggesting slipped mispairing as the deletion mechanism. Postmortem examination revealed a small nose with anteverted nares, generalized micromelia, and a small thorax with protuberant abdomen; radiography showed platyspondyly with pedicle width exceeding that of the vertebral bodies, a narrow, bell-shaped chest, and the 'Schneckenbecken sign' of both iliac wings (snail-like appearance due to medial bone projection from the inner iliac margin). All long bones were short and stocky with some metaphyseal flaring, and tarsal ossification was advanced.</Attribute>
        <Citation Type="general">
          <ID Source="PubMed">19508970</ID>
        </Citation>
      </ObservedData>
    </ObservedIn>
